    "updated_at": "2016-09-06T10:44:29Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "So doing `df.index.B` looks simple and generally it is, however there are some edge cases that make this untenable:\n\n`df.index['B']` needs to work similarly for a smooth user xp, however this is in direct conflict with positional access on a single level for a regular `Index` and on a MI:\n\n```\nIn [7]: df.index[0]\nOut[7]: (1, 1)\n\nIn [8]: df.index[[True]*len(df.index)]\nOut[8]: \nMultiIndex(levels=[[1, 2], [1, 2, 3]],\n           labels=[[0, 0, 0, 1, 1], [0, 1, 2, 0, 1]],\n           names=[u'A', u'B'])\n```\n\nYou might think that is ok, until you realize that 0 _also_ could mean level=0. Then what do you do?\n"
